{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14134"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14134"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.27,0.1,0.46,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52717"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6814"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2585"},{"type":"tags","id":"2979"},{"type":"tags","id":"3402"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5408"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44990"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52717"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic to receive her stool culture results. Five days ago, she presented with diarrhoea, abdominal cramps, and fever. She works as a chef in a busy restaurant. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reports her symptoms have improved, with only two loose stools in the past 24 hours. She would like to return to work as soon as possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Stool culture confirms Salmonella infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding work restrictions for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Return to work with strict hand hygiene","Return to work after symptom free and stool culture negative","Return to work after completing antibiotic course","Return to work after symptom-free for 48 hours","Return to work after symptom-free for seven days"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient, a food handler diagnosed with Salmonella gastroenteritis, requires appropriate work restrictions to prevent the spread of infection. The most appropriate advice is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eexclude from work for 48 hours after symptoms resolve\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach balances the need to prevent transmission with practical considerations for the patient and their employer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReturning to work immediately with strict hand hygiene\u003C/strong\u003E is not sufficient to prevent the spread of Salmonella given the patient currently remains symptomatic. While hand hygiene is crucial, it alone cannot guarantee prevention of transmission, especially in a food handling environment where the risk of contamination is high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReturning after symptom free and negative stool culture\u003C/strong\u003E is overly cautious for most cases of infectious diarrhoea. While this approach would ensure the patient is no longer shedding the bacteria, it may take a prolonged period to obtain a negative stool culture, which is unnecessarily restrictive. This may be a requirement of certain, more severe infections such as Shiga-toxin producing\u003Cem\u003E E. coli.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReturning to work after completing antibiotic course\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best approach. Antibiotics are not generally not indicated for the management of infectious gastroenteritis or colitis unless the illness is clinically severe or the patient is at a higher risk of complications (e.g. immunosuppression).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcluding from work for seven days regardless of symptom resolution\u003C/strong\u003E is overly restrictive and not necessary in most cases. While some individuals may continue to shed the bacteria for several weeks, the risk of transmission significantly decreases after symptoms resolve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to work restrictions, other important measures include notifying public health authorities, emphasizing proper hand hygiene (especially after using the toilet and before handling food), thorough cleaning and disinfection of potentially contaminated surfaces, and avoiding preparing food for others until fully recovered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that some jurisdictions may have specific guidelines for food handlers with confirmed Salmonella infection. Always consult local public health guidelines for the most up-to-date recommendations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Food handlers diagnosed with Salmonella gastroenteritis should be excluded from work until 48 hours after symptoms resolve.","Public health authorities should be notified of Salmonella cases in food handlers to prevent potential outbreaks."],"references":["Communicable Diseases Network Australia. CDNA Guidelines for the Investigation and Management of Food Handlers during Non-typhoidal Salmonella Outbreaks. In: Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care [online]; 2012. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/cdna-national-guidelines-for-the-investigation-and-management-of-food-handlers-during-non-typhoidal-salmonella-outbreaks","Queensland Health. Food Handler Exclusion Guidelines. 2017. Available at: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0036/684495/food-handler-exclusion-guide.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14134"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T12:09:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T12:11:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6814"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52717"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"t